        "text": "<@UBN9AFS0N>\n\n&gt; the `=` on the clauses seems to be a star, but after main it's missing\nThis is intentional. There's not a 1:1 correspondence between the textual symbols and visual symbols. If fizz is written using MultiWayIf (which is slightly closer to the visual representation since Glance only has expressions, not declarations) the = in the clauses become -&gt;\n\n```fizz' x = if\n  | x `mod` 15 == 0 -&gt; \"FizzBuzz\"\n  | x `mod` 3  == 0 -&gt; \"Fizz\"\n  | x `mod` 5  == 0 -&gt; \"Buzz\"\n  | otherwise       -&gt; show x```\n&gt; in flow diagrams there's a standard symbol for alternative\nIs this symbol a diamond? The symbols for the if expression (the half filled circle and the star) are fairly arbitrary, so most any two distinct shapes could work here.\n\n&gt; instead of wrapping everything in boxes, using parenthesis to delimit \"boxes\"\nGreat suggestion, I'll try this out.\n\n<@UBKNXPBAB>\n\n&gt; Mathematicians have a notation for case-by-case analysis. [...] Is there a reason not to follow a path closer to this?\nI think replacing the conditional symbol (half filled circle) with \"if\", and the value symbol (orange star) with \"then\" could work. One difference from the math notation is that oftentimes the value symbol is below the conditional. The bracket is problematic because it would cross over wires going left to right.",
